The paper deals with the decidability of the existential theory of equations in free groups with rational constraints, which is a topic in logic and algebra. Therefore, cs.LO (Logic in Computer Science) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also presents an algorithm that works in polynomial space, which is a topic in computational complexity, making cs.CC (Computational Complexity) another likely sub-category. The use of regular word languages in the specification of the constraints suggests that cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) could also be a relevant sub-category. The paper also deals with free monoids with involution, which is a topic in algebraic topology, making cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory) a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper may also be relevant to cs.CG (Computational Geometry) due to the use of free groups, which are often used in geometric group theory.
